data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code is a **timeout enforcement** pattern. In .NET 8, `Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort()` is a no-op. The fix is cooperative cancellation via `CancellationToken`.

### Key Problems in the Original Code

| .NET Framework API | .NET 8 Status |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` (`SYSLIB0006`) |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown by the runtime |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | No-op / obsolete |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes <paramref name="work"/> with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the token for cancellation to be responsive.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            Task<T> task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Overload for work that cannot accept a CancellationToken (fire-and-forget
    /// semantics — the work continues running after timeout but the caller stops
    /// waiting). Use the CancellationToken overload whenever possible.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        Task<T> task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // WaitAsync throws OperationCanceledException when the token fires,
            // even though the underlying task keeps running.
            return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Critical Pitfalls

**1. Cancellation is cooperative, not preemptive.**
The work *must* check the token. A CPU-bound loop that ignores it will never stop:

```csharp
// ❌ BAD — will never respond to cancellation
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    while (true) { /* spin */ }
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// ✅ GOOD — checks the token at each iteration
executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        DoChunk();
    }
    token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
    return 42;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

**2. The `Func<T>` overload (no token) is a leaky abstraction.**
`Task.WaitAsync` stops *waiting* but the underlying work keeps running on the thread pool. Use this only when you can't modify the work delegate.

**3. Always dispose `CancellationTokenSource`.**
It allocates an internal timer when created with a timeout. The `using` statement prevents timer leaks.

**4. Don't swallow `OperationCanceledException`.**
The `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch your own timeout, not an unrelated cancellation from an outer scope.

**5. `AggregateException` wrapper removed.**
`Task.Run` already wraps faulted work. `GetAwaiter().GetResult()` unwraps it to the original exception, preserving the stack trace — better behavior than the original code.

### Caller Migration

```csharp
// Before (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveWork(), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// After (.NET 8) — preferred: pass token through
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    token => ExpensiveWork(token), 
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```
